if points went out of the initailized size ,what happens

If the coordinates go outside the size of the 2D array, your program may access memory that doesn't belong to the array. This is called out-of-bounds access and can cause:

Garbage values
Wrong output
Program crash (segmentation fault)
Unpredictable behavior
Example

Suppose:

#define ROWS 20
#define COLS 40
char canvas[ROWS][COLS];

Valid indices are:

Rows: 0 to 19
Cols: 0 to 39

If you do:

canvas[25][10] = '*';
then you're accessing outside the array.

How to Prevent It

Before drawing, check whether the rectangle fits:

if(row >= 0 && col >= 0 &&
   row + height <= ROWS &&
   col + width <= COLS)
{
    drawRectangle(row, col, width, height);
}
else
{
    printf("Rectangle is outside canvas!\n");
}
Or check each point before writing:

if(i >= 0 && i < ROWS &&
   j >= 0 && j < COLS)
{
    canvas[i][j] = '*';
}
In Exams

A common safety check is:

if(x >= 0 && x < ROWS &&
   y >= 0 && y < COLS)
{
    canvas[x][y] = '*';
}
This ensures that any line, rectangle, triangle, or circle is drawn only within the initialized canvas.
